<br>
“Hello?” Her voice came across more exhausted than she would have liked.<br>
<br>
“Hi Sara, it’s Grissom.” That got her attention. She was suddenly very alert.<br>
<br>
“Hey, what’s up?” She asked, trying to keep it casual. She knew the call would have something to do with work, even though she hoped it didn’t, but any more information on the case would be a good thing too.<br>
<br>
“I know it’s your day off, but I’m going to need you to come into work tonight,” he calmly stated. He wasn’t sure how she was going to take this information. He didn’t want her to think he was getting in the way of her personal life, even though he was, but he rationalized that the case was a justifiable scapegoat.<br>
<br>
“Why?” He sighed. He should have expected her to at least ask why he would be making her come in on her day off, even if under normal circumstances she wouldn’t have.<br>
<br>
“A formal investigation is being launched against Ecklie and Roberts. I need you and Warrick to do everything you can to get your murder case closed up.”<br>
<br>
“So you’re making Warrick come in too?” Grissom briefly shut his eyes, wincing at the image that Sara had just put in his head. ‘Of course, they’re still going to be together, but not on a date, it’s work, and neither one of them would let personal feelings get in the way of their work. They wouldn’t.’ He tried to reassure himself. “Gris? You still there?” Grissom hadn’t realized that he had paused for such a time to give Sara concern.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, still here. And yes, I left a message on Warrick’s machine that he needs to come in tonight too. So get some sleep, because I’m going to need your best tonight.” Sara almost snorted at the double entendre that conjured in her mind.<br>
<br>
“Okay, see you tonight then,” she said, and hung up the phone. Grissom had at least expected a good-bye. He hoped she wouldn’t hold this against him for too long. An angry Sara made for a difficult working environment.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
That evening, Warrick strolled into work. His cool demeanor was apparent as always, but it was obvious that sleep deprivation was starting to take its toll on him. Catherine raised an eyebrow at him as he came into the break room.<br>
<br>
“Hey Catherine,” he greeted, with an upward nod of his head. She looked concerned.<br>
<br>
“I thought you and Sara were going to dinner tonight,” she said, although it came out as more of a question. Warrick raised his eyebrows at her and shook his head.<br>
<br>
“Man, no secrets around this place are there?” He said with a roll of his eyes. “It was just a friend thing,” he started to explain, and Catherine gave him an understanding smile with a look that told him to continue. He shrugged. “Got a message on my machine from Gris saying that he needed me to come in tonight because of the case.” Catherine stared at him, but was contemplating something in her head. This didn’t go unnoticed. “What?”<br>
<br>
“What?” She questioned back, trying to seem innocent. He tilted his head slightly.<br>
<br>
“What aren’t you telling me?” She smiled and got up from her chair. She walked past him to the opening to the hallway and looked both ways to make sure no one was listening, and then she turned back to him.<br>
<br>
“He likes her,” she explained in a calm voice. She wasn’t sure how to talk to Warrick about this. If he liked Sara as more than a friend, then telling him that Grissom did too probably wouldn’t bode well. Warrick surprised her by giving a grin and nodding.<br>
<br>
“I know. Glad I’m not the only one who’s noticed.” Catherine was genuinely taken aback.<br>
<br>
“You know?” She asked almost angrily. “Then why did you ask her out?” Warrick sighed and motioned for her to sit down. She took one last look out into the hallway, and then sat down, directing her attention to Warrick, who had also taken a chair.<br>
<br>
“I asked her as a friend thing,” Warrick paused and smiled. “And to maybe make Grissom jealous enough to take action. Their intermittent flirting was really getting to me for some reason.” Catherine’s eyes grew large, but gleefully so.<br>
<br>
“You planned this?! Oh my God, Warrick!” She looked around again after realizing that she had practically shouted. “I can’t believe you didn’t tell me, you know I would have helped you,” she said a little quieter. Warrick grinned.<br>
<br>
“Well, you still can,” Warrick said, “seeing as how nothing’s happened yet.” A devious smile crawled upon Catherine’s lips and she nodded.<br>
<br>
“I’m in.” Warrick just smiled.<br>
<br>
“You’re in what?” Nick asked casually as he walked into the break room. Catherine and Warrick shot each other an ‘oh, crap’ look and then tried to cover by plastering fake grins on their faces and changing the topic.<br>
<br>
“Hey Nicky,” Catherine greeted. “Didn’t see you there.” He eyed her suspiciously and walked over to where she was sitting. He leaned his hand against the table and hunched over to look directly at her.<br>
<br>
“You’re in what?” He drawled. Catherine still tried to maintain her fake grin and looked over at Warrick for any assistance. He just shrugged.<br>
<br>
“Go ahead, just don’t tell him in the building,” Warrick said, getting up. “Gotta go find Sara, see what else we can dig up on this case.” He walked out the door. Nick cocked an eyebrow at him and then returned his attention to Catherine. He seemed to temporarily put aside what his previous question was.<br>
<br>
“You know what’s going on with them?” He asked Catherine. She got up from her seat and put a hand on his shoulder.<br>
<br>
“Come on, we’ve got work to do. We can gossip in the car.” She gave him a real smile, which he returned, but with a confused look on his face.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, well, you’d better tell me everything,” he walked quickly to catch up to her. “I hate being the last one to find out about things around here.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Warrick found Sara and Grissom in the lab.<br>
<br>
“Wow, big surprise to see you guys here,” he said sarcastically. Sara smiled and chuckled. Grissom gave him a look that could only be interpreted as territorial. He noticed that Grissom moved closer to Sara after he came in, and he just grinned. “Anything new?” He had already been filled in on the Ecklie situation, but he figured that Sara had come in early, as always, and might have come up with something that he didn’t know yet. Sara beamed.<br>
<br>
“Yep,” she answered. Grissom tried to avoid eye contact with Warrick, and kept his eyes focused on whatever was under the microscope. “And you’re never going to believe it.” Warrick raised an eyebrow. She paused and looked at him, half expecting him to try and guess what the evidence was.<br>
<br>
“You’ve been hanging around Greg too much Sara,” Warrick said, just wanting her to spit out what they had learned.<br>
<br>
“Humph, I wish,” Greg mumbled. Both Warrick and Grissom shot a warning look in his direction. His eyes grew large and he wheeled his chair a little bit in the opposite direction. “What?” Grissom’s eyes squinted at him and Greg turned his attention back to what he was doing. Sara grinned and looked at Warrick, practically oblivious to the interaction that had just taken place in front of her.<br>
<br>
“There was a better DNA sample on the lollipop stick than there was on the candy itself,” Sara smiled. “And you’ll never guess who it matches.” Warrick furrowed his brow.<br>
<br>
“Fellowes?” Sara, still smiling, shook her head. Grissom looked up from the microscope at Warrick and grinned.<br>
<br>
“Ecklie,” Grissom stated. Warrick’s eyes grew large in shock. Sara glared at Grissom.<br>
<br>
“I wanted to tell him,” she said, half way hurt. Grissom gave her a soft look and shrugged.<br>
<br>
“You were taking too long.” Sara narrowed her eyes and kiddingly punched him on the arm. He smiled at her. ‘This is good,’ he thought, ‘she doesn’t seem upset that I drug her away from her date, and she’s engaging in adolescent mating ritual behavior with me, maybe she and Warrick really are just friends.’<br>
<br>
“Where did you get a sample of Ecklie’s DNA?” Warrick asked, breaking the moment between Sara and Grissom. Sara turned her attention back to him.<br>
<br>
“Get this, it was already on file from a case four years ago. Apparently he was one of the suspects in an evidence tampering investigation. He was cleared, but the committee still took the suspicion into consideration when they were considering candidates for the job Grissom has now.” Grissom grinned. Sara was smart; she had found the old DNA sample and had the idea to test the lollipop stick as well, all in the hour that she had arrived early for work.<br>
<br>
“So Ecklie killed Thomason?” Warrick asked with surprise. Grissom frowned.<br>
<br>
“Not necessarily.” He shook his head. “But it does mean that he was at the victim’s house…”<br>
<br>
“Which is enough for a warrant for his house,” Sara finished. Grissom grinned again. Working with her felt right. Being with her felt right. She was finishing his thoughts again. Warrick nodded in understanding.<br>
<br>
“Cool.” He looked at Grissom eyeing Sara and decided to put his plan back into action. “So do we still get the rest of the night off?” Grissom’s head whipped around and he turned a little paler.<br>
<br>
“What?”<br>
<br>
“Sara and I were supposed to have the night off. Since you have new evidence on Ecklie…” Grissom shot him an authoritative glare and smirked.<br>
<br>
“Nice try Warrick,” Grissom said. “After you get the warrant, I want you and Sara to go over with Brass to Ecklie’s house and get everything you can.” Sara grinned at Grissom.<br>
<br>
“He was just kidding Gris.” Grissom looked at her, she had an honest, almost loving, expression on her face that he would have loved to give in to, but just couldn’t yet, not until he knew for sure that they were just friends.<br>
<br>
“You’d better get going.” Warrick rolled his eyes at Sara and she smiled. She came around the counter to him and latched her arm with his. Grissom’s expression fell.<br>
<br>
“We’d better get going,” Sara mimicked Grissom’s words and giggled. Warrick grinned. His plan was back on schedule. They walked out of the lab, leaving a confused Grissom and Greg in their wake.<br>
<br>
“What was that?” Greg asked, dumbfounded. Grissom shook his head.<br>
<br>
“Got me.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Nick and Catherine were on their way to Chris Edwards’s apartment. He had been pestering her for information since they got in the vehicle, but she didn’t say anything until they were half way there. He looked over at her from the driver’s seat when they were at a red light and gave her his best puppy dog eyes. She laughed and threw her hands in the air in mock surrender.<br>
<br>
“Fine! I’ll tell you. What do you want to know?” Nick grinned and continued driving.<br>
<br>
“What do you know about Warrick and Sara?” She shook her head.<br>
<br>
“You can’t tell Grissom or Sara,” she started. He peered at her through the corner of his eyes.<br>
<br>
“Sara? Wouldn’t she already know what’s going on?”<br>
<br>
“Uh, no, not exactly.” Nick was intrigued. He shot her a pressing look. “Warrick asked Sara out as a friend thing, that part is true.” He nodded. “But, he also did it because he thought it might make Grissom hop off the fence as far as asking Sara out.” Nick’s eyes grew wide.<br>
<br>
“What?” Nick asked in astonishment. Catherine smiled and shrugged.<br>
<br>
“I guess he got sick of them flirting all the time but not doing anything about it,” she reasoned. Nick pulled over in front of Edwards’s apartment building.<br>
<br>
“When were they flirting? And, oh…” Nick paused, remembering what Sara had let slip the previous day.<br>
<br>
“Oh?” Nick smiled and turned to face Catherine.<br>
<br>
“Sara and I were talking in the car the other day, there was a misunderstanding, she thought I was saying that she was interested in Grissom and flipped out when I said I’d have to tell him that,” Nick rambled. Catherine’s smile grew bigger.<br>
<br>
“Really?” Catherine asked. “Interesting.” Nick shook his head.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, but don’t you think he’s a little old for her?” Catherine shot him a warning look. “Okay, okay, to each his own, I get it. Ya’ ready?” He motioned toward the apartment building and they gathered their supplies.<br>
<br>
“You remember to call for backup?”<br>
<br>
“Of course,” Nick answered as they made their way into the building. “We’ll just have to wait to go in until they get here.” Catherine nodded and pushed the elevator button.<br>
<br>
“Third floor right?” Nick raised his eyebrows in affirmation. After they got off the elevator, they saw two police officers waiting in the hallway by one of the apartments. Nick did a quick head nod toward them.<br>
<br>
“Hey! How’d you guys get up here before us?” He asked as they made their way down the hall. “I didn’t see your car parked out front.” One of the officers grinned.<br>
<br>
“Parked on the back side of the building, easier access to Owens,” the officer replied.<br>
<br>
“Ah. Well, shall we?” Nick questioned. They agreed and rang the small buzzer on the door. A few thundering footsteps vibrated as the man came to answer his door. Catherine and Nick exchanged a silent look, and Catherine ran her fingers over the gun in her holster. Chris Edwards was not a man who was small, or even average, in size or stature. Nick looked up at the goliath standing in front of them. He was at least 6’6” and looked like he had worked out every day of his life. Instead of a normal greeting, he simply let a small growl out. Catherine decided that she’d better be the one to speak or a fight could break out.<br>
<br>
“Mr. Edwards? I’m Catherine Willows with the Las Vegas Crime Lab, we have a warrant to search your apartment,” she said simply, and she thought, authoritatively, as she handed him the warrant. He scowled at her, and didn’t move out of the doorway. Instead he bore his eyes into her. Catherine, despite being able to stand up for herself in most situations, felt very intimidated by the man, and motioned to her gun with her hand again. His eyes peeled away from her and he stepped back into the apartment, leaving the door open for them to come inside. Nick noticed some pictures on the wall of Edwards’ in a wrestling outfit, and, as usual, tried to strike up a conversation to see if he could get additional information.<br>
<br>
“You used to be a wrestler?” He managed what could pass for a social smile at the man. Edwards glared back at him.<br>
<br>
“Used to be,” he answered. His low, gravely voice, only added to the aura of creepy danger that surrounded him. Nick nodded and turned away from him, deciding that it would be safer to try and collect evidence. He had a feeling that the sooner they got out of there, the better.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Sara and Warrick waited on the stoop outside of Ecklie’s house, waiting for Brass to arrive with the warrant.<br>
<br>
“You’re in a good mood,” Warrick observed. “Wouldn’t have anything to do with Grissom paying attention to you again would it?” He grinned and she grinned back.<br>
<br>
“I don’t know where you’re getting that Warrick,” her grin turned into a smile. “I’m just in a good mood. Don’t you ever get good moods?” He raised his eyebrows.<br>
<br>
“Sure, but mine don’t revolve around Grissom,” he kidded. Sara rolled her eyes, and then noticed Brass getting out of his car.<br>
<br>
“Took you long enough Brass,” she called out to him. He smiled as he jogged up to them.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, sorry about that,” he said when he finally reached them. “When you first called and said you needed a warrant for Ecklie’s house because you found his DNA at the murder scene, I thought I was just having a good dream.” He smiled again. Sara nodded.<br>
<br>
They rang the doorbell. There was no answer. They waited another minute and then rang it again. This time, they heard a voice cursing on the inside of the house, telling them to hold on. Ecklie opened the door. He shot a virulent look at Brass and held out his hand.<br>
<br>
“Warrant?” He asked. Brass obliged and handed him the warrant as Warrick shoved past him. He wanted as little to do with the man as possible, especially after seeing the way he had treated Sara the other day. He made a mental note to not leave Sara in the same room with Ecklie without Brass or himself being there too. Ecklie leered at Sara as she walked into the house.<br>
<br>
“If you wanted to get inside my house Sidle, you could have just said so the other day,” he sneered. Sara had to fight the wave of repulsion that coursed through her body with his statement, and just ignored him, going to the other room. Ecklie smirked. It was so easy to get a reaction from her, even if she didn’t use words. Warrick had heard the comment and shot Ecklie a warning look, to which, Ecklie responded by rolling his eyes.<br>
<br>
“Calm down sport, I didn’t touch your girlfriend,” he said, ignoring any response that Warrick may have given, he went to the position he had been in before they had rung the bell, sitting in his reclining chair watching television. Warrick was starting to fume, but he shook it off. If they did find any evidence that implicated Ecklie in Thomason’s murder, then he would be out of their lives for a long time. He smiled at this thought. Brass came over to Warrick as he was looking through cabinets in the front room.<br>
<br>
“Your girlfriend?” He asked, in a hushed tone, just in case he had heard Ecklie incorrectly. Warrick stared up at him from his crouching position on the floor. He gave a little grin.<br>
<br>
“Kind of a long story,” he answered, and then went back to going through the cabinet drawers. Brass raised his eyebrows in surprise, and then decided to check on Sara. He found her in Ecklie’s bedroom.<br>
<br>
“Last place you ever thought you’d be huh?” He asked, although it was more of a statement in response to the evident disgust on her face. She smiled at him.<br>
<br>
“Tell me about it,” she answered, as she sifted through his hamper. She was wearing clear plastic glasses and latex gloves, spraying generous amounts of luminol on every item of clothing. “Can you hit the lights?” He nodded and switched the lights off. It was dark, but he could see her smile as she picked up a pair of pants from the pile that were glowing. He flipped the light switch back on.<br>
<br>
“Find what you were looking for?” She looked over at him with her gap- toothed smile, and proudly held the pair of pants up. They didn’t have any visible blood on them, so Sara reasoned that he had probably tried to clean them. He grinned back at her. “You want me to get Warrick?” She pushed the pants into a large evidence bag.<br>
<br>
“Nope, I’ll do it. Thanks though.” She smiled again as she passed by him and went toward the living room. He grinned to himself. ‘Kind of an odd couple, but she sure seems to be happier than usual, so it must be working.’<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Edwards was a less than gracious host. Not that anyone who was having their house searched for evidence linking them to a murder would be gracious, but some people would stay out of the way. Not Chris Edwards. After the first ten minutes, he started hulking around Catherine. Nick and the two officers had him back off more than once. Nick was digging through the closet when he found a pair of sneakers buried under several other pairs, but the pair he found had blood on the bottoms of them. He smiled. There hadn’t been anything else in the apartment to suggest that Edwards had anything to do with the murder, but he didn’t want to get rid of his $200 Nikes. He bagged them and walked out to the small bathroom, where Catherine was still dusting and swabbing.<br>
<br>
“Hey,” he said, the cheer evident in his greeting. Catherine whipped her head around to see Nick holding up the bag with the shoes in it. She smiled. Edwards got angry.<br>
<br>
“Those are mine,” he stated in an even voice that was tinged with anger ready to explode.<br>
<br>
“Sir, the warrant we gave you gives us the ability to search your home and take any evidence we find with us,” Nick explained in a cool voice, attempting to calm Edwards down. Edwards glared at Nick, and then reached to his side. He grabbed Catherine by her neck. The officers jumped to attention, aimed their guns, and told him to let her go. Both Nick and Catherine looked panicked. Nick had been in situations before where he had been the one who was threatened or harmed, but to have to watch it happen to one of his friends was a different story. “Let her go!” Edwards shook his head.<br>
<br>
“You take something of mine, I take something of yours,” Edwards said in a collected voice. Then he slammed Catherine’s head onto the ceramic sink. Blood splattered and she was unconscious. The two officers responded immediately by shooting him. They had to shoot him several times before he finally went down. Nick crouched down by Catherine’s body and yelled at the officers.<br>
<br>
“Call an ambulance!” The officers looked at each other. “Now!”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Sara and Warrick had already made it back to the lab when Sara’s cell phone rang.<br>
<br>
“Sidle.” Sara listened to Nick recall the entire incident to her. Throughout the conversation, Warrick watched Sara’s bubbly exterior fall to fearful and sullen. “Did you tell Grissom yet? Okay, Warrick and I will be right there.” She pressed the button to end the call.<br>
<br>
“What’s going on?” Warrick asked, following an already moving Sara down the hallway. He noticed that she was upset and that her hands had started to shake. He placed a hand on her shoulder to stop her. “Sara?” She turned to face his direction, but refused to meet his eyes.<br>
<br>
“The case Nick and Catherine were on…” she paused. “The suspect got angry, they couldn’t stop him in time…” Warrick’s expression dropped as he paid close attention to what Sara was going to say next. She finally looked in his eyes. “Catherine’s hurt, she’s in the hospital, it’s not good. Can we go now?” She asked in desperation. Warrick was in shock, and all he could do was nod, following Sara out to the car.<br>
<br>
Sara saw Nick pacing in the waiting area. She went over to him and gave him a big hug.<br>
<br>
“Have you heard anything yet?” Nick shook his head. Sara noticed that Warrick looked panicked. She walked over to him and placed a reassuring hand on his arm. “She’s going to be okay.” The statement came out sounding more unsure than Sara would have liked. He closed his eyes and sighed. Acting on emotion alone, he wrapped his arms around her. She rested her head on his chest; still holding back the tears she knew would come eventually. She and Catherine weren’t best friends, but she had been getting along better with her. Now she was silently thinking that she might not ever get the chance to really get to know her. For Sara, working with death had dulled the fact that life is a fragile thing, when for most people it would have done the opposite.<br>
<br>
Grissom came down the opposite end of the hallway, after questioning the nurse endlessly about Catherine’s condition. Nick was the first to call out to him. Grissom acknowledged him with a raise of his eyebrows, and then directed his attention toward Warrick, who was still holding Sara in his arms.<br>
<br>
“Anything yet?” Warrick asked hopefully. Grissom stared at him blankly, a gesture that the others misinterpreted as shock at Catherine’s situation. “Gris?” Grissom raised his eyes a little in response to hearing his name, and then shook his head.<br>
<br>
“The nurse said her vitals were strong, but she’s still unconscious. She’ll send the doctor over when she gets out.” Sara smiled a dull smile.<br>
<br>
“A woman doctor, Catherine will be glad,” she said approvingly. Warrick grinned. They still had one arm around each other, and he leaned down to give her a chaste kiss on the top of her head. Grissom frowned, and went to sit down on a chair in the waiting area. Nick and the others followed. Nick watched the interaction between Sara and Warrick as they sat next to each other. They were both impatiently flipping through the old magazines that were lying out, and then handing them off to the other person.<br>
<br>
He silently wondered to himself if Warrick’s plan hadn’t backfired on him, with the two falling for each other. He was sure that that their comfort ability with being around each other wasn’t faked, and that neither one of them was cruel enough to intentionally put more misery on Grissom, with one of his best friends already lying in a hospital bed. His thoughts, and everyone else’s, were put on hold when the doctor came over.<br>
<br>
“Hi, I’m Dr. Bettis, are you Ms. Willows’s friends?” They nodded and Grissom shook her hand.<br>
<br>
“How is she doing?” He asked, bracing himself for the worst.<br>
<br>
“Her skull was fractured in three spots. The first two were small fractures, but the third could cause lasting damage. I expect it to heal on its own, but she may need plastic surgery to correct it.” She paused, waiting for them to digest the information. “We were able to control the bleeding, and when she wakes up, she’ll most likely have a bad concussion and some possible memory loss,” she explained.<br>
<br>
“But she’ll be okay?” Nick asked nervously. Dr. Bettis gave a compensory grin and nodded.<br>
<br>
“Barring any further complications, I expect her to make a full recovery eventually. But,” she was quick to add, “she won’t be able to go back to work for a while, and she’ll need a strong support system to help take care of her for a couple of weeks.” Sara nodded and lightly elbowed Warrick in the ribs.<br>
<br>
“It’s covered,” she answered. Warrick eyed her, and then ran a hand over his face.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, no problem,” he said. Dr. Bettis gave a quick nod. Grissom observed the interaction. He knew that Sara and Catherine weren’t close, but he was happy to see her making an effort to be there for her.<br>
<br>
“They’re moving her out of the E.R. to a regular room now, you should be able to see her after that.” She looked at her watch. “I’d give it a half hour.” They agreed and Dr. Bettis left. Sara got fidgety after they sat down again.<br>
<br>
“Problem Sara?” Grissom asked, staring her down. She bounced out of her chair, still fidgeting with her hands.<br>
<br>
“I can’t just sit here Grissom, I feel useless,” Sara explained. As much as he didn’t want to see her go, Grissom conceded.<br>
<br>
“They won’t let you use your cell phone in here.” Sara shot him a ‘duh’ look. “Why don’t you go out side and call Greg? See if he’s come up with anything on the evidence you and Warrick brought back from Ecklie’s place?” Sara sighed in relief.<br>
<br>
“On it,” she said, as she quickly made her way to the exit. Grissom let his head fall. Warrick tried to be reassuring.<br>
<br>
“She’ll be okay, Catherine’s a fighter.” Grissom’s eyes darted up to Warrick’s. He saw concern, empathy, and maybe a little fear, although he doubted Warrick would ever admit that. Grissom took off his glasses and rubbed his eyes and the bridge of his nose with one hand. He said nothing to Warrick in response, he didn’t need to.<br>
