Sara flipped out her cell phone the second she got outside, and hurriedly called Greg.<br>
<br>
“Lab, this is Greg,” he answered, still looking at the computer.<br>
<br>
“Hey Greg, it’s Sara. You got anything on those pants yet?” She looked around. Despite being outside, she was still a little jumpy.<br>
<br>
“You know how long it takes to match up blood results? How much other work I’ve had dumped on me from day shift?” He rambled, twirling a pencil in his fingers.<br>
<br>
“God, Greg, do you have anything yet or not?!” Sara quipped, then wiped her arm over her forehead, brushing her hair out of her face. “Sorry, it’s been a bad day,” she apologized. Greg seemed more taken aback by the apology than the snipe.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, I know,” he remarked in a quieter voice. “Prelim results match your vic, but that’s just typing, not DNA,” he explained. Sara nodded to herself.<br>
<br>
“Anything else?”<br>
<br>
“Well, if Nick’s there with you, which I presume he is, tell him the blood on the shoes came back with mixed results.” Sara furrowed her brow in a quizzical manner.<br>
<br>
“What do you mean?”<br>
<br>
“Looks like the shoes have two different kinds of blood on them, one of the types matches the victim in that case, the other doesn’t. You want the weird part?” He paused and she sighed in frustration. “Fine. The second blood type doesn’t match either suspect. In fact, it looks like there was a first layer on there and then a second. Creepy. If nothing else, you’d think this guy would rinse off the bottom of his expensive shoes.” Sara shook her head.<br>
<br>
“I guess.” She didn’t really feel like putting up with Greg’s eccentricities. “Thanks Greg, I’ll tell Nick.” She hung up on him. She took in a deep breath and started to turn around when she saw Jimmy Estes to the side of her, only she saw him too late. He covered her mouth and nose with a chloroform-covered cloth, and then caught her unconscious body. Her cell phone dropped to the ground. He carried her to a waiting car, shoving her in the back. He got in the passenger seat and nodded to the driver.<br>
<br>
“Let’s go.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Grissom kept looking at the door Sara had gone through as he paced back and forth. Nick grinned.<br>
<br>
“It’s a good thing the floor is tiled, if they had carpet you’d have worn a hole in it by now,” he said lightheartedly. Grissom gave him a serious look.<br>
<br>
“She should have been back by now,” he stated. Nick shrugged.<br>
<br>
“You’re the one who told her to get out of here,” he received another warning glare. “Okay, maybe she just went to get coffee somewhere good. The stuff here is terrible.” He winced at the cup in his hands and put it down. Grissom sighed and his demeanor loosened a little.<br>
<br>
“If you’re want her to come back in, why don’t you just go tell her?” Warrick asked, not looking up from the magazine he was skimming through. Grissom shook his head.<br>
<br>
“I want to be here when they come to tell us what room Catherine’s in.” Warrick nodded.<br>
<br>
“You could call her,” he said. Grissom stared dully at him and Warrick raised his eyes. He motioned to the courtesy phone with his head. Grissom gave a small grin in thanks and walked over to the phone, dialing Sara’s cell phone number. He listened impatiently as it kept ringing with no answer. He furrowed his brow. He knew she had it with her, why wasn’t she answering? Finally, a voice picked up, but it wasn’t Sara’s.<br>
<br>
“Hello?” The crease in Grissom’s brow deepened, in anger and in worry.<br>
<br>
“Who is this?” He demanded.<br>
<br>
“Calm down dude,” the male voice said on the other end. Grissom was too impatient to roll his eyes. “I just found this phone on the ground outside the hospital. I don’t know where the owner is.” Grissom’s features dropped.<br>
<br>
“What?” He wanted to make sure he had heard correctly, and that his mind wasn’t playing tricks on him. With everything that had happened over the last few days, his head was already starting to spin from sleep deprivation and trying to solve too many puzzles at once.<br>
<br>
“The owner of the cell phone isn’t here man,” the boy said. “I’m going to turn it into lost and found, so I’m going to hang up on you now okay?” He said in a condescending voice, as if trying to calm Grissom on the other end. Grissom hung up the courtesy phone.<br>
<br>
“Sara’s gone,” he gazed in Nick and Warrick’s direction, but not at either one of them. “Someone found her cell phone out front.” The manner of his speech was eerily calm. He was trying to figure out what was going on. He knew that Sara had been shaken by Catherine’s situation, but she would never just up and leave like that. Even if Greg had found something amazing in the results, she would have come in and told him that she was leaving, and if not him then Warrick. He inwardly cringed that he had even thought that.<br>
<br>
Nick and Warrick, however, became very worried compared to Grissom’s deceivingly calm exterior.<br>
<br>
“What do you mean she’s gone?” Warrick asked, standing up. “She wouldn’t take off. She and Catherine aren’t best friends, but she was just as worried about her as we are.” Nick nodded and crossed his arms.<br>
<br>
“I don’t see her doing something like that either,” he added. “But who would take Sara?” Warrick shot a pointed look at him.<br>
<br>
“You think somebody took her?” Nick shrugged.<br>
<br>
“Well, we all agree that she wouldn’t just leave, right? And I know she wouldn’t leave without her cell phone, she’s practically surgically attached to that thing.” Grissom and Warrick exchanged worried glances, and then Grissom’s turned to panick.<br>
<br>
“Where is Ecklie?” Nick and Warrick looked at each other.<br>
<br>
“Dunno. Home?” Warrick answered. Grissom stared unbelievingly at him. “I don’t follow the man around Gris, and charges haven’t been brought against him.” Grissom closed his eyes for a moment.<br>
<br>
“He took her.” Nick raised an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“Why would Ecklie take Sara?” Warrick sighed and shook his head.<br>
<br>
“Long story man, long story,” he answered. Grissom made his way to the courtesy phone again and called Brass.<br>
<br>
“I had him put out an APB on Sara,” he flopped into the unwelcoming chair. “I shouldn’t have let this happen,” Grissom stated, the burden of the situation weighing heavily on him.<br>
<br>
“It wasn’t your fault Gris,” Warrick said reassuringly and placed a hand on Grissom’s shoulder for a second. He hung his head down. “If anyone’s to blame it’s me. I should have gone outside with her. She was upset, she probably wasn’t paying attention to her surroundings. It’s the Holly and Nick thing all over again, I shouldn’t have let her go out alone,” he replied solemnly, his voice full of self blame. Warrick ran his hands over his face and then crossed his arms. Grissom took off his glasses and rubbed his eyes again.<br>
<br>
“It’s not your fault Warrick,” he said, thinking that he wished it were, so he could have someone to blame but himself. “I’m the one who told her to go outside and call Greg.” His eyes regained a little sparkle. “Nick, call Greg and find out what he told Sara.” Nick went to the phone in the lobby. “Warrick, try to think of any place that Ecklie might take Sara. If it was him, then it may have something to do with the case you were working on.” Warrick raised his eyebrows, but decided not to comment, rather to just go along with Grissom’s effort to regain control over the situation. A hospital volunteer approached the men, as they were busy with their different chores.<br>
<br>
“Hi. You’re waiting to see,” he paused, “Catherine Willows?” Grissom nodded, and the man continued. “Okay, she’s in room 403. Do you need instructions on how to get there?”<br>
<br>
“No,” Grissom answered rather gruffly. “We’ll just follow the signs, thanks.” The man plastered a fake smile onto his face.<br>
<br>
“Okay, but if you change your mind, anyone at the nurses’ stations can help you,” he said, turning around to walk the other way, he rolled his eyes.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Catherine lay still in her hospital bed, tubes running fluids into her veins. Nick sat down next to her and held her hand, apologizing over and over again. Grissom sat down as well, but Warrick seemed put on edge by seeing Catherine in that position.<br>
<br>
“Warrick?” Grissom asked, then motioning with his eyes for Warrick to sit down. Warrick raised his eyebrows and shot Grissom a skeptical look, then glanced at Catherine.<br>
<br>
“It shouldn’t have happened,” he said, almost under his breath. Nick looked up at him, thinking that Warrick was placing the blame on him for the incident.<br>
<br>
“There wasn’t anything I could do. She’s gonna be fine though, you heard the doc.” Warrick sighed.<br>
<br>
“I wasn’t talking about Catherine, well, I was, but I meant the whole thing,” he rambled. Grissom narrowed his eyes.<br>
<br>
“What do you mean Warrick?”<br>
<br>
“It just feels like these last few days, it seems like we’ve been set up somehow, like somebody is pulling the strings.” He sat down.<br>
<br>
“Explain.” Grissom could only take so much, and Warrick’s rambling wasn’t helping his oncoming headache.<br>
<br>
“Doesn’t it seem interesting to you that Ecklie was involved in the Thomason murder? And then he was hitting on Sara and she shot him down and now she’s missing?” Grissom and Nick exchanged glances.<br>
<br>
“You think this has all been some big conspiracy of some kind?” Grissom asked in a tone that was disbelief mixed with amusement at Warrick’s hypothesis. Warrick stared back at him, and after a brief pause, he got up again.<br>
<br>
“What the hell was she thinking liking you?” Warrick mumbled. Grissom furrowed his brow in confusion. Warrick made his way over to Catherine’s bedside and leaned down to give her a kiss on the forehead. “Get well soon pretty.” Then he started to leave.<br>
<br>
“Where are you going?” Nick asked.<br>
<br>
“To get Sara back,” he replied in a determined voice. Grissom got up to follow him. He caught him in the hall and grabbed his arm. He looked down, as if he didn’t know what to say to Warrick. “Something wrong?” Grissom looked up at him.<br>
<br>
“Everything,” he sighed. Warrick’s expression held compassion for his friend.<br>
<br>
“Gris, you know I care about Catherine,” he started, and Grissom nodded.<br>
<br>
“You’re good friends. It really seems like she’s taken you under her wing.” Warrick inwardly winced, but only because it was true. There was only so much he could do to make her notice him, really notice him, and so far she hadn’t. She had seen all of his gestures as friendship, or maybe as mentor/student, but had never indicated that she returned his feelings.<br>
<br>
“Yeah, but there’s nothing I can do for her, she’s already getting good care from the hospital staff, and you and Nick are here to talk to her,” he paused, carefully wording what would come next. “But Sara is out there somewhere, with Ecklie or not, she’s missing. She needs me.” Grissom felt his heart drop, but decided to finally make effort.<br>
<br>
“No, she doesn’t Warrick,” he said, ignoring Warrick’s narrowed eyes. “She needs me.” Warrick just stared blankly at him for a moment, caught off guard by Grissom’s statement, and then a small grin crept onto his face.<br>
<br>
“Well, glad you finally realized it.” Confusion swept over Grissom’s features.<br>
