<br>
“Way to go Sidle.” Sara turned and lifted her head as much as possible to see the man, but she didn’t need to, having recognized the voice.<br>
<br>
“Ecklie! You son of a bitch! Let me out of here!” Sara let her emotions get the best of her temporarily, but quickly switched tactics. “You might get less time if you voluntarily release me.” Ecklie laughed.<br>
<br>
“I’m not going to be serving any time Ms. Sidle, nice try at the whole negotiating thing though,” he mocked. He walked closer to her and looked down at her, and she looked angrily back at him. She glanced around at what little she could see of the room.<br>
<br>
“The least you could do is push me back up,” she said, trying her best to keep her voice calm. From what she had seen, it didn’t look or smell like Ecklie’s house, and she wanted to know where she was, reasoning that it might help her chances at escaping. Ecklie raised an eyebrow, but then shrugged, pushing her back up. He was standing much too close to her for comfort. Of course, if Sara had a choice, he wouldn’t be on the same continent as she was. Sara got a better look around and furrowed her eyebrows.<br>
<br>
“This isn’t your house,” she stated, a confused tone to her voice. A creepy smirk swept across Ecklie’s face.<br>
<br>
“No, it’s your boyfriend’s place,” he responded. Letting out a chuckle, he said, “Guess you two usually go to a motel or your place since you didn’t recognize his bedroom right off.” He kept grinning. “Or do you not usually make it that far?” Ecklie leaned in and Sara turned her face away from him, repulsed and angry. “Oh yeah,” he ran a finger along her cheek and she snapped her head away from him. “I could easily see you being a kink.” He smiled and pulled back a little.<br>
<br>
Sara fought the urge to spit at him, knowing that repercussions would immediately follow. The longer she could keep him talking, the longer she could postpone anything else that he might have in mind. She inwardly grimaced at the thought.<br>
<br>
“So tell me Sara,” he drew out her name and she glared at him. “What made you decide to go out with Warrick Brown?” He said Warrick’s name in disgust.<br>
<br>
“What made you decide to kill an innocent woman, frame your accomplice, and then kidnap me?” She shot back, although still in a normal volume. It had turned into an obvious power struggle, and although Ecklie clearly had the physical advantage, Sara would be damned if she’d let him have the intellectual one. The least she could do was find out why all of this had happened, so she could have some resolution before Ecklie killed her. Ecklie smiled an evil, lecherous smile, and Sara did everything in her power not to wince. He leaned again.<br>
<br>
“Only one innocent woman? Tsk, tsk. Your investigative skills are slipping Sidle. Guess working and sleeping with Brown have clouded your mind a little, huh?” He chuckled and walked over to another chair that was facing her, one that looked considerably more comfortable than the one Sara was tied to. He sat down and leered at her. “Such a waste.” She narrowed her eyes. Two could play this game.<br>
<br>
“Well, since you think I’m so incompetent and you’re going to kill me anyway,” she paused and Ecklie smiled. “Why don’t you tell me what’s actually going on?” He put his hands together, pondering the request. He put on a serious face and leaned forward.<br>
<br>
“Haven’t you ever wondered Sidle? I know you have.” He arched an eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“Wondered what?” Ecklie’s demeanor didn’t change. He kept staring at her with his cold eyes.<br>
<br>
“What it’s like on the other side,” he started to explain. “Every person has the capability for good or evil. Haven’t you ever wondered, after working all these cases, being around all these dead bodies, getting into all these killers’ heads? Haven’t you ever wondered what it would be like?” Sara’s face paled. When she first learned that Ecklie might be involved, she thought he might be trying to advance his career somehow, or it had been a lovers’ quarrel gone wrong, she hadn’t imagined that he had turned into a sociopath. The evidence that had just been presented to her made her skin crawl and set every nerve in her body on edge. She barely managed to shake her head.<br>
<br>
“No. I’ve never wondered what it’s like to kill someone,” she stated, the fear apparent in her voice. Ecklie grinned slightly and leaned back in his chair.<br>
<br>
“That’s a shame. It’s kind of a rush. Knowing that you can take another life, and take care of the crime scene so it looks like it was someone else. It’s an intense sensation,” he said in all seriousness. Sara felt nauseous and panicked. She surmised that he probably brought her to Warrick’s place so he could plant evidence to make it look like Warrick had been the one to kill her. She knew for sure now that he would kill her, and probably do unspeakable things to her beforehand. Her only hope was that Grissom and the others had noticed her disappearance and were looking for her, and that they would find her in time.<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Grissom and Warrick were driving toward Ecklie’s house to meet up with Brass, who already had units searching the city for Ecklie and Sara. Warrick’s phone rang.<br>
<br>
“Warrick.”<br>
<br>
“Hey, is Grissom there with you? I heard about what’s going on. I tried to call him, but his phone is giving an out of area or power off signal. Have you found her?” Greg rambled. Warrick turned to Grissom.<br>
<br>
“Hey Gris, turn your phone back on.” Grissom frowned and got his cell phone out. He had forgotten to turn it back on after they left the hospital.<br>
<br>
“Crap! How could I be so stupid? She could have been trying to call me.” Warrick shook his head.<br>
<br>
“She would have tried to call me next, and Greg’s the only one who’s called.” He heard a sigh come from the other end of the phone.<br>
<br>
“Speaking of which, I’m still here,” Greg said in an annoyed tone.<br>
<br>
“Sorry. Anything new?” Warrick asked. Greg smiled.<br>
<br>
“As a matter of fact, yes, and thank you for asking. You know how the second set of blood on Edwards’s shoes?”<br>
<br>
“No,” Warrick said in confusion.<br>
<br>
“Oh, I guess Sara didn’t get a chance to tell you,” Greg said regretfully. “Anyway, there was a second set of blood on Chris Edwards’s shoes, and you’ll never guess who it belongs to.”<br>
<br>
“Who?” Warrick squirmed a little in the passenger’s seat. He was growing impatient and they were almost at Ecklie’s house.<br>
<br>
“Your vic, Thomason,” he stated in a proud voice. Warrick’s eyebrows raised.<br>
<br>
“What?”<br>
<br>
“Oh wait, it gets better,” Greg said, clearly excited by the information. “It also had a third set of DNA mixed in with the muck, but I did the analysis and it’s semen, not blood.”<br>
<br>
“But she didn’t have any semen found in or around her body,” Warrick said.<br>
<br>
“Well, what do I know? Maybe he stepped on the trash with the condom in it or something,” Greg hypothesized. “Anyway, get this, it wasn’t Edwards’s or Estes’s semen. It was Ecklie’s.” Warrick’s stomach fell.<br>
<br>
“Are you sure?” He asked, concerned.<br>
<br>
“99.78% match, probably would have been better if it wasn’t mixed in with the two blood samples,” Greg responded. “What’s wrong? I thought this new piece of information would be good news.” Warrick sighed and looked over at Grissom.<br>
<br>
“It is and it isn’t. We think Ecklie’s the one behind Sara’s abduction.”<br>
<br>
“I thought they said Jimmy Estes was the one who showed up on the hospital’s videotape?”<br>
<br>
“Yeah, but we think Estes is only hired help, that Ecklie’s the one behind it, and with this new information,” Warrick paused and shook his head, processing what was going on. It had been a long road, but he felt that Sara and he were finally starting to be friends. ‘Maybe even more than friends eventually if Grissom wasn’t in the picture.’ He sighed again. “Greg, I’ve got to go, we’re at Ecklie’s place.” He turned off the phone without waiting for Greg’s reply. Greg sat in the lab, his face buried in his hands, trying to keep from crying.<br>
<br>
Grissom and Warrick met with Brass by the front of the house.<br>
<br>
“There’s no one here,” Brass said with regret. “Anywhere else he could have taken her?” Grissom frowned.<br>
<br>
“We already checked her place,” Grissom answered.<br>
<br>
“And units are going to every seedy motel in the city, just in case,” Brass added. Everyone was worried, time was running out and they still had nothing.<br>
<br>
“Too bad they left Sara’s phone behind,” Warrick mumbled, but Grissom heard him.<br>
<br>
“Why?” Warrick shrugged.<br>
<br>
“It would have been a long shot anyway I guess. I’ve been working on a new triangulator program on my computer at home, it can tell where someone’s cell phone is, and therefore, probably that person, with just the number, they don’t need to make a call.” Grissom’s eyes grew wide. “I already asked Sara if I could try it out with her phone, her number’s already in the system, but I haven’t gotten a chance to test it yet.” Grissom stared at him blankly.<br>
<br>
“We have Ecklie’s cell phone number.” Grissom tilted his head. Warrick grinned and nodded.<br>
<br>
“Let’s go.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Sara sat in the chair, still trying to loosen her restraints, while Ecklie sharpened a long knife. He looked over at her.<br>
<br>
“This should be fun. It always is when they put up a fight.” He grinned an evil grin. Sara tried to ignore him, but it was growing harder.<br>
<br>
“It would be more of a fight if I wasn’t tied up,” she said, knowing that he would never agree to it. He smiled.<br>
<br>
“Maybe after we christen Warrick’s bed,” his eyes grazed over her body and she paled again. ‘They’ll find me, they’ll find me.’ Ecklie shook his head a little as if reading her thoughts. “They’ll find you sweetheart, just not before we have some fun, and not alive,” he sneered. Sara started shaking slightly, but she managed to calm it down to the point where Ecklie didn’t appear to notice.<br>
<br>
“They’ll know you were responsible, you’re going to prison,” Sara stated, getting her nerve up again. “We already have evidence that you were involved in Thomason’s murder, even if they can’t prove the others.” ‘Even if they can’t prove this one,’ she thought ruefully. Ecklie just nodded, which wasn’t the response she was expecting.<br>
<br>
“One last hurrah then,” he said, coming closer to her with the sharpened knife. He didn’t hear the key turning in the front door lock, but he did hear Warrick and Grissom when they came in.<br>
<br>
“It’s in the office,” Warrick said and Grissom nodded, following him quickly down the hall. They may not have even noticed Ecklie and Sara if Ecklie hadn’t reacted. He had one hand over her mouth and the other clutching the knife at her throat.<br>
<br>
“Just in time to watch your girlfriend die,” Ecklie said in a loud voice, commanding the attention of the two men. Warrick and Grissom froze, their eyes large and focused on the scene in front of them. Sara silently begged them with her eyes and Grissom nodded.<br>
<br>
“Put the knife down Ecklie,” Grissom took a few steps forward. “It’s over.” Ecklie rolled his eyes, but his nervousness showed. He began to sweat. “Let her go.” Ecklie was so concentrated on Grissom that Warrick had been able to make his way back into the living room to call Brass. He hoped they would get there in time. Ecklie suddenly noted Warrick’s disappearance.<br>
<br>
“Looks like your boyfriend chickened out Sidle,” he laughed, a nervous, crackly laugh. Grissom shook his head.<br>
<br>
“Warrick isn’t her boyfriend Ecklie.” Ecklie grinned his evil grin.<br>
<br>
“Wow, so the all mighty Grissom doesn’t know everything. Interesting.” Grissom took another step forward, but stopped moving when Ecklie pulled the knife closer to Sara’s neck, drawing a little blood from the first few layers of skin.<br>
<br>
“You think Warrick is her boyfriend because he told you she was taken,” Grissom paused, stalling for time. “He didn’t say by whom.” Ecklie narrowed his eyes at him. Grissom looked at Sara. She looked back at him with a mixture of confusion and surprise and he gave her a small grin. She understood. He turned his attention back to Ecklie. “Put the knife down.” Ecklie shook his head.<br>
<br>
“No way. She dies today.” Two units pulled up to the house with lights but no sirens. They came charging through the open front door, Brass quickly following them. Warrick motioned to the bedroom, but said nothing, and Brass nodded. “She dies now.” He started to slowly run the blade across Sara’s neck and she whimpered in pain. Three shots rang out, and Ecklie fell to the floor. Grissom ran over to Sara and hugged her. She grinned.<br>
<br>
“Don’t suppose you could untie me so I can go to the hospital?” His expression fell to worry and he looked at the cut on her neck. It was starting to bleed more than he had originally seen. He glanced back up at her and she had passed out.<br>
<br>
“Get an ambulance!” Brass nodded.<br>
<br>
“Already on the way.”<br>
<br>
~*~*~*~<br>
<br>
Grissom slept in a chair in Sara’s hospital room. She woke up and smiled at him, then winced at the pain it caused in her neck. She ran her fingers over the bandage remembering what had happened.<br>
<br>
“Gris,” she whispered. He didn’t move. “Grissom,” she said a little louder, but not so the nurses outside the room could hear. The room was dark and she could see that it was night. ‘Of course, my body’s set on that schedule now,’ she thought. He stirred a little. “Grissom wake up,” she finally said, as close to her normal speaking volume as possible. His eyes cracked open and he grinned.<br>
<br>
“Sara.”<br>
<br>
“Grissom.” She smiled brightly. He moved his chair so he was right next to her bed. She chuckled. “Geez Grissom, you may as well just sit on the bed,” she said half sarcastically. He cocked an eyebrow at her and she looked the other way to hide the blush that had covered her cheeks. “So how is Catherine?”<br>
<br>
“She’s fine. She woke up, slight concussion, no discernable memory loss. Could have been a lot worse.” Sara nodded. “Warrick’s going to help take care of her until the concussion passes.” Sara smiled.<br>
<br>
“He has a crush on her you know.” He grinned.<br>
<br>
“I thought he liked you,” he admitted in a hushed voice. “It nearly killed me to see him with you like that.” She took his hand and he looked up at her.<br>
<br>
“He knew I was taken.” He nodded, leaned in, and kissed her.<br>
<br>
Change was scary, but good once they got there.<br>
<br>
